'''Adrian Lamo''' is a [[Threat_(computer)#Threat_analysis|threat analyst]] and &quot;[[grey hat]]&quot; [[Hacker (computer security)|hacker]].  He first gained media attention for breaking into several high-profile computer networks, including those of ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Yahoo!]], and [[Microsoft]], culminating in his 2004 arrest.&lt;ref name=kahn&gt;[http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/12.04/hacker_pr.html Wired 12.04: The Homeless Hacker v. The New York Times]. Wired.com. Retrieved on 2011-03-10.&lt;/ref&gt;  In 2010, Lamo became embroiled in the [[WikiLeaks]] scandal involving [[Bradley Manning]], who was arrested after Lamo reported to federal authorities that Manning had [[internet leak|leak]]ed hundreds of thousands of sensitive U.S. government documents.&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite web
  | last = Poulsen
  | first = Kevin
  | authorlink = Kevin Poulsen
  | last2 = Zetter
  | first2 = Kim
  | authorlink2 = Kim Zetter
  | title = U.S. Intelligence Analyst Arrested in Wikileaks Video Probe
  | publisher = [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]
  | date = June 6, 2010
  | url = http://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2010/06/leak/
  | accessdate = June 7, 2010}}
&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite news
  | title = US intelligence analyst arrested over security leaks
  | publisher = BBC
  | date = June 7, 2010
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/world/asia_pacific/10254072.stm
  | accessdate = June 7, 2010}}
&lt;/ref&gt;

==Personal==
Lamo was born in [[Boston, Massachusetts]] to Mario Lamo and Mary Lamo-Atwood in 1981.&lt;ref name=&quot;mpalm03&quot;&gt;
{{cite web
  | last = Palmquist
  | first = Matt
  | authorlink = Matt Palmquist
  | title = A Duty to Hack
  | publisher = [[SF Weekly]]
  | date = April 16, 2003
  | url = http://www.sfweekly.com/2003-04-16/news/a-duty-to-hack/
  | accessdate = October 23, 2006}}
&lt;/ref&gt;  He spent his early childhood in [[Arlington, Virginia|Arlington]], [[Virginia]], until moving to [[Bogot√°, Colombia|Bogot√°]], [[Colombia]] around the age of 10. When his family moved back to the [[United States]] two years later, they settled in [[San Francisco]], where Adrian lived until he tested out of high school a year early. Popularly called the &quot;homeless hacker&quot; for his transient lifestyle, Lamo spent most of his travels [[CouchSurfing|couch-surfing]], squatting in abandoned buildings and traveling to [[Internet cafe]]s, libraries and universities to investigate networks, and sometimes exploiting security holes.&lt;ref name=kahn /&gt; Despite performing authorized and unauthorized [[vulnerability assessment]]s for several large, high-profile entities, Lamo refused to accept payment for his services. 

In the mid-1990s, Lamo became a volunteer for the gay and lesbian media firm [[PlanetOut.com]].&lt;ref&gt;http://www.wired.com/culture/lifestyle/news/2002/03/50811?currentPage=1&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/12.04/hacker_pr.html&lt;/ref&gt; In 1998, Lamo was appointed to the Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, Queer and Questioning Youth Task Force by the [[San Francisco]] [[Board of Supervisors]].&lt;ref&gt;http://www.worldtribune.com/worldtribune/WTARC/2010/ss_military0732_08_02.asp&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite web
  | title = Agenda &amp; Minutes Archive
  | publisher = [[San Francisco Board of Supervisors]]
  | date = August 3, 1998
  | url = http://www.sfbos.org/index.aspx?page=2723
  | accessdate = October 23, 2010
  | quote = Adrian Lamo, Seat No. 10}}
&lt;/ref&gt;  

During this period, in 2001, he overdosed on prescription amphetamines.&lt;ref name=&quot;mpalm03&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;jkahn04&quot;/&gt;

In a 2004 interview with ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'', an ex-girlfriend of Lamo's described him as &quot;very controlling,&quot; stating, &quot;He carried a [[electroshock weapon|stun gun]], which he used on me.&quot; According to the same article, a court issued a restraining order against Lamo.&lt;ref name=&quot;jkahn04&quot;&gt;
{{cite web
  | last = Kahn
  | first = Jennifer
  | authorlink = Jennifer Kahn
  | title = The Homeless Hacker v. The New York Times
  | publisher = [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]
  | year = 2004
  | url = http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/12.04/hacker_pr.html
  | accessdate = July 8, 2010}}
&lt;/ref&gt; Lamo disputed the accuracy of the article and wrote, &quot;I have never been subject to a restraining order in my life&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
  | last = Lamo
  | first = Adrian
  | title = Citability (is important!)
  | publisher = God, Sex, &amp; the FBI: Adrian Lamo's (alleged) blog
  | date = July 10, 2010
  | url = http://pax.vox.com/library/post/citability-is-important.html
  | accessdate = July 10, 2010}}{{Dead link|date=October 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In May 2010 Lamo reported his backpack stolen. The investigating officer noted unusual behavior by Lamo and detained him. He was diagnosed with [[Asperger syndrome|Asperger's syndrome]] after having been placed on a 72-hour involuntary psychiatric hold, which was extended to a total of nine days.&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite web
  | last = Poulsen
  | first = Kevin
  | authorlink = Kevin Poulsen
  | title = Ex-Hacker Adrian Lamo Institutionalized for Asperger‚Äôs
  | publisher = [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]
  | date = May 20, 2010
  | url = http://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2010/05/lamo/
  | accessdate = May 23, 2010}}
&lt;/ref&gt;

As of March 2011 he is in hiding, stating that his &quot;life was under threat&quot; after turning in Bradley Manning.&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite web
  | title = Hacker: Why I turned FBI Informer
  | publisher = Al Jazeera
  | accessdate = March 16, 2011
  | url = http://english.aljazeera.net/video/americas/2011/03/2011313202019296426.html
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Activities==
Lamo first became known operating [[AOL]] watchdog site [[Inside-AOL.com]].&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite web
  | last = Brown
  | first = Janelle
  | authorlink = Janelle Brown
  | title = Can AOL silence its critics?
  | publisher = [[Salon.com]]
  | date = July 1, 1999
  | url = http://archive.salon.com/tech/log/1999/07/01/inside_aol/
  | accessdate = February 1, 2006}}
&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite web
  | last = Poulsen
  | first = Kevin
  | authorlink = Kevin Poulsen
  | title = Hijackers take AIM accounts
  | publisher = [[SecurityFocus]]
  | date = November 29, 2000
  | url = http://www.securityfocus.com/news/119
  | accessdate = February 1, 2006}}
&lt;/ref&gt;

===Security compromise===
In February 2002 he broke into the internal computer network of ''The New York Times'', adding his name to the internal database of expert sources, and using the paper's [[LexisNexis]] account to conduct research on high-profile subjects. The Times filed a complaint, and a warrant for Lamo's arrest was issued in August 2003 following a 15 month investigation by federal prosecutors in New York. At 10:15 AM on September 9, after spending a few days in hiding, he surrendered to the [[United States Marshals Service|US Marshals]] in [[Sacramento, California]]. He re-surrendered to the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] in New York City on September 11, and pled guilty to one felony count of [[computer crime]]s against [[Microsoft]], [[LexisNexis]] and ''[[The New York Times]]'' on January 8, 2004.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.wired.com/techbiz/it/news/2004/01/61831  &quot;Adrian Lamo Cuts Deal With Feds&quot;], ''Wired.com'', January 9, 2004.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.securityfocus.com/news/7771  &quot;Lamo Pleads Guilty to Times Hack&quot;], ''SecurityFocus'', January 8, 2004.&lt;/ref&gt; 

Later in 2004, Lamo was sentenced to six months detention at his parents' home plus two years probation, and was ordered to pay roughly $65,000 in restitution. He was convicted of compromising security at ''[[The New York Times]]'' and [[Microsoft]],&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite web
  | last = Lemos
  | first = Robert
  | authorlink = Robert Lemos
  | title = Hacker helps Excite@Home toughen defenses
  | publisher = [[CNET News]]
  | date = May 29, 2001
  | url = http://news.com.com/2100-1001-261728.html
  | accessdate = January 21, 2006}}
&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite web
  | last = Poulsen
  | first = Kevin
  | authorlink = Kevin Poulsen
  | title = Proxy exposes Excite@Home data
  | publisher = [[SecurityFocus]]
  | date = May 5, 2001
  | url = http://www.securityfocus.com/news/209
  | accessdate = April 24, 2006}}
&lt;/ref&gt; [[Yahoo!]]&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite web
  | last = Poulsen
  | first = Kevin
  | authorlink = Kevin Poulsen
  | title = Yahoo! News hacked
  | publisher = [[SecurityFocus]]
  | date = September 9, 2001
  | url = http://www.securityfocus.com/news/254
  | accessdate = January 21, 2006}}
&lt;/ref&gt; and [[MCI Inc.|MCI WorldCom]].&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite web
  | last = Poulsen
  | first = Kevin
  | authorlink = Kevin Poulsen
  | title = Lamo's Adventures in WorldCom
  | publisher = [[SecurityFocus]]
  | date = December 5, 2001
  | url = http://www.securityfocus.com/news/296
  | accessdate = January 21, 2006}}
&lt;/ref&gt;

When challenged for a response to allegations that he was glamorizing crime for the sake of publicity, his response was &quot;Anything I could say about my person or my actions would only cheapen what they have to say for themselves&quot;. When approached for comment during his criminal case, Lamo frustrated reporters with [[non sequitur (absurdism)|non sequiturs]] such as &quot;Faith manages&quot;,&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite web
  | last = McCullagh
  | first = Declan
  | authorlink = Declan McCullagh
  | title = The 'homeless hacker' talks
  | publisher = [[CNET News]]
  | date = September 16, 2003
  | url = http://news.com.com/2008-1014_3-5076942.html
  | accessdate = January 21, 2006}}
&lt;/ref&gt; (probably a reference to science fiction television show [[Babylon 5]]) and &quot;It's a beautiful day.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite web
  | last = McCullagh
  | first = Declan
  | authorlink = Declan McCullagh
  | title = Judge lifts hacker's PC restrictions
  | publisher = [[CNET News]]
  | date = September 12, 2003
  | url = http://news.cnet.com/Judge-lifts-hacker%27s-PC-restrictions/2100-1002_3-5076124.html
  | accessdate = January 21, 2006}}
&lt;/ref&gt;

At his sentencing, Lamo expressed remorse for harm he had caused through his intrusions, with the court record quoting him as adding &quot;I want to answer for what I have done and do better with my life.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite web
  | last = Poulsen
