'''AymƒÅq''' ({{lang-fa|ÿß€åŸÖÿßŸÇ}}), also transliterated as ''Aimak'' or ''Aimaq'', are a collection of [[Persian language|Persian]]-speaking [[nomad]]ic or semi-nomadic tribes of [[Iranian people|Iranian]]{{citation needed|date=January 2011}} stock. They are found throughout the north and northwest [[Highland (geography)|highland]]s of [[Afghanistan]], immediately to the north of [[Herat]], and in the [[Khorasan Province]] of [[Iran]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite encyclopedia |last= Janata|first=A. |editor= [[Ehsan Yarshater]]|encyclopedia= [[Encyclop√¶dia Iranica]]|title= AYMƒÄQ|url=http://www.iranica.com/newsite/index.isc?Article=http://www.iranica.com/newsite/articles/unicode/v3f2/v3f2a038.html |edition= Online Edition|publisher= [[Columbia University]]|location= United States}}&lt;/ref&gt; They speak a number of subdialects of the [[Aimaq dialect]] of [[Persian language|Persian]]. 

Aimaks were originally known as ''chahar'' (&quot;four&quot;) Aymaqs:  the [[Taimani]] (the main element in the population of [[Ghor]]), the [[Ferozkohi]], the [[Temuri]], and the [[Jamshidi (tribe)|Jamshidi]].  Other sources state that the &quot;Aimaq-Hazara&quot; are one of the ''Chahar'', with the Temuri instead being of the &quot;lesser Aimaqs&quot; or ''Aimaq-e digar''&lt;ref name=&quot;Vogelsang2002&quot;&gt;{{cite book|author=Willem Vogelsang|title=The Afghans|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=9kfJ6MlMsJQC&amp;pg=PA37|accessdate=1 April 2011|year=2002|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|isbn=9780631198413|pages=37‚Äì}}&lt;/ref&gt; (&quot;other Aimaqs&quot;) along with the Tahiri, Zuri, Maleki, and Mishmast.&lt;ref name=&quot;Khanam2005&quot;&gt;{{cite book|author=R. Khanam|title=Encyclopaedic ethnography of Middle-East and Central Asia: A-I|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=q_189OeDwSMC&amp;pg=PA24|accessdate=1 April 2011|year=2005|publisher=Global Vision Publishing Ho|isbn=9788182200623|pages=24‚Äì}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Origin and classification==
Aimaks are closely related to [[TƒÅjik people|Tajiks]] and [[Hazara people|Hazara]] in varying degrees. In the Afghan [[census]], Aimaks are classified as Tajiks.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.nps.edu/Programs/CCs/Ghor/Ghor.html Aimak, Ghor province on NPS]&lt;/ref&gt; Aimaks live in parts of western and central Afghanistan, making up the majority in [[Ghor Province|Ghor]], and also live in large numbers in the western areas of [[Herat Province|Herat]] and [[Badghis Province|Badghis]], and to a lesser extent in [[Farah Province|Farah]], [[Faryab Province|Faryab]], [[Jowzjan Province|Jowzjan]], and [[Sar-e Pol Province|Sar-e Pol]]. The word &quot;AymƒÅq&quot; is Mongolian meaning &quot;tribe&quot; or &quot;grazing territory&quot;. Attempts to link it somehow with Ancient Iranian semi-god patriarch Yima or Jamshid lack both linguistic and historical foundations.

==Demographics==
Estimates of the Aimaq population vary between 250,000 and 2 million. They are [[Sunni]] Muslims, in contrast to the Hazara, who are [[Shia]]s. The Temuri Aimaqs are of Mongolian origin, apparent in their physical appearance and their housing (Mongolian-style [[yurt]]s).&lt;ref&gt;&quot;Afghanistan&quot;. Encyclop√¶dia Britannica. Ultimate Reference Suite.  Chicago: Encyclop√¶dia Britannica, 2008.&lt;/ref&gt; However, the Taimanis, Ferozkohis, and Jamshidis are of non-Mongolian origins and refer to themselves as Tajik; the majority of the Aimaqs in Afghanistan are from these latter three sub-groups.

