==Etymology and cultural significance==
The name of the star derives from [[Ancient Greek]] ŒëœÅŒ∫œÑŒø·ø¶œÅŒøœÇ (''Arktouros'') and means &quot;Guardian of the Bear&quot;,&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3D*%29arktou%3Dros ŒëœÅŒ∫œÑŒø·ø¶œÅŒøœÇ], Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott, ''A Greek-English Lexicon'', on Perseus&lt;/ref&gt; ultimately from ·ºÑœÅŒ∫œÑŒøœÇ (''arktos''), &quot;bear&quot;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Da%29%2Frktos ·ºÑœÅŒ∫œÑŒøœÇ], Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott, ''A Greek-English Lexicon'', on Perseus&lt;/ref&gt; + Œø·ΩñœÅŒøœÇ (''ouros''), &quot;watcher, guardian&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dou%29%3Dros2 Œø·ΩñœÅŒøœÇ], Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott, ''A Greek-English Lexicon'', on Perseus&lt;/ref&gt; This is a reference to it being the brightest star in the constellation Bo√∂tes (of which it forms the left foot), which is next to the Greater and Lesser Bears, [[Ursa Major]] and [[Ursa Minor]]. 

In [[Arabic language|Arabic]], it is one of two stars called ''al-simƒÅk'' &quot;the uplifted one&quot;, the other being [[Spica]]. Arcturus, then, is ÿßŸÑÿ≥ŸÖÿßŸÉ ÿßŸÑÿ±ÿßŸÖÿ≠ ''as-simƒÅk ar-rƒÅmiƒß'' &quot;the uplifted one of the lancer&quot;.  The term '''Al Simak Al Ramih''' was appeared in Al Achsasi Al Mouakket catalogue, which  was translated into [[Latin]] as '''Al Simak Lanceator'''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal
 | last=Knobel | first=E. B.
 | title=Al Achsasi Al Mouakket, on a catalogue of stars in the Calendarium of Mohammad Al Achsasi Al Mouakket
 | journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society
 | volume=55 | page=429 | month=June | year=1895
 | bibcode=1895MNRAS..55..429K }}&lt;/ref&gt; This has been variously [[Romanization|romanized]] in the past, leading to obsolete variants such as '''Aramec''' and '''Azimech'''. The name '''Alramih''' is used in [[Geoffrey Chaucer]]'s ''[[Treatise on the Astrolabe]]'' of 1391. Another Arabic name is '''Haris-el-sema''', from '''ÿ≠ÿßÿ±ÿ≥ ÿßŸÑÿ≥ŸÖÿßÿ°''' ''ƒßƒÅris al-samƒÅ‚Äô'' &quot;the keeper of heaven.&quot;&lt;ref name=arabicstar&gt;[http://www.jas.org.jo/arabic/alma.html List of the 25&amp;nbsp;brightest stars], website of the Jordanian Astronomical Society, accessed March 28, 2007.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=allen&gt;Richard Hinckley Allen, ''Star-names and their meanings'' (1936), p. 100-101.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=arabicdict&gt;Hans Wehr (J.M. Cowan ed.), ''A dictionary of modern written Arabic'' (1994).&lt;/ref&gt; or ''' ÿ≠ÿßÿ±ÿ≥ ÿ£ŸÑÿ¥ŸÖŸÑ''' ''ƒßƒÅris al-shamƒÅl‚Äô'' &quot;the keeper of north.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;Davis Jr., G. A., [http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1944PA.....52....8D &quot;The Pronunciations, Derivations, and Meanings of a Selected List of Star Names,&quot;]''Popular Astronomy'', Vol. LII, No. 3, Oct. 1944, p. 13.&lt;/ref&gt;

In [[Chinese astronomy]], Arcturus is called ''Da Jiao'' (Â§ßËßí, Great Horn, [[Pinyin]]: D√†ji«éo), because it is the brightest star in the [[Chinese constellation]] called ''[[Horn (Chinese constellation)|Jiao Xiu]]'' (ËßíÂÆø, Pinyin: Ji«éo Xi«î). And later, it become a part of ''Kang Xiu'' (‰∫¢ÂÆø, Pinyin: K√†ng Xi«î), which is also a Chinese constellation. 

Ancient [[Japan]]ese astronomy adopted the Chinese name ''Da Jiao'' (Â§ßËßí, ''Ro'ku too''), but its western name, Arcturus („Ç¢„É´„ÇØ„Éà„Ç•„É´„Çπ), is more common now.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}

In [[Inuit astronomy]], Arcturus is called the Old Man (''Uttuqalualuk'' in [[Inuit]]) and The First Ones (''Sivulliik'' in [[Inuit]]).

It corresponds to the [[Hindu calendar|Hindu]] astronomy [[Nakshatra]] of [[Swati the Star|Swati]].
[[Image:Redgiants.svg|thumb|right|200px|Comparison between Arcturus, red supergiant [[Antares]], and the Sun. The black circle is the size of the orbit of Mars.]]

In Indonesia, Arcturus is called ''Bintang Biduk'' (Star of boat).

* ''[[1933 World's Fair]]''. The star achieved fame when its light was used to open the [[Century of Progress|1933 Chicago World's Fair]]. The star was chosen as it was thought that light from Arcturus had started its journey at about the time of the [[World's Columbian Exposition|previous Chicago World's Fair]] in 1893 (as the star is 36.7&amp;nbsp;light years away the light had, actually, started its journey in 1896).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | title = Century of Progress World's Fair, 1933-1934 | publisher = University of Illinois-Chicago | date = 2008-01 | url = http://collections.carli.illinois.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/uic_cop&amp;CISOPTR=45&amp;CISOBOX=1&amp;REC=1 | accessdate = 2009-09-06}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Myths==
This bright star is the subject of numerous ancient and modern myths.

* ''[[Ancient Greece]]''. In Greek mythology, Arcturus is a star created by [[Zeus]] to protect the nearby constellations Arcas{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}} and Callisto ([[Ursa Major]] and [[Ursa Minor]]). According to the myth, Callisto was the daughter of Lycaon, the king of Arcadia. As a young girl, she vowed to the goddess [[Artemis]] to be forever faithful and devoted to her. She was to remain a virgin forever in order to serve and accompany Artemis while hunting animals in the forest. However, one day, Zeus, the king of the gods, fell in love with Callisto and raped her. Callisto gave birth to a son whom she named Arcas. Zeus knew that if Hera, his wife, learned of his disloyalty she would be angry with Callisto, so in order to protect her he transformed her into a brown bear. Callisto, as a bear, roamed around the forest looking for her son. After years of searching she found Arcas, who was now a grown man. She finally came upon him and, overjoyed, stood on her hind legs and tried to embrace him. Arcas, however, did not recognize his mother and thought he was being attacked, so he drew his sword to defend himself. Zeus, watching everything, as usual, felt sorry for them and in order to prevent this tragedy he transformed Callisto and Arcas into constellations (now known as Ursa major and Ursa minor) and placed them near to him in the sky. Hera, who had learned the truth and was furious, asked [[Ocean]], the river that surrounds the earth, not to permit them to wash themselves in his waters; therefore these two constellations are always seen high in the night sky, and never drop into the ocean. Moreover, in order to protect them from Hera's jealousy, Zeus placed another star near to them: Arcturus (which means the guardian of Arctos, the bear). It protects and accompanies them for eternity.{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}}

* ''Occult traditions''. In the [[astrology]] of the [[Middle Ages]], Arcturus was one of the 15&amp;nbsp;[[Behenian fixed stars]], associated with [[jasper]] and the [[plantago|plantain]] herb. [[Cornelius Agrippa]] lists its symbol [[Image:Agrippa1531 Alchameth.png]] under the alternate name '''Alchameth'''.{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}}

* In Indian [[Astrology]] or [[Jyoti·π£a|Vedic Astrology]] or [[Sidereal astrology|Sidereal Astrology]], Arcturus is called ''''[[Swati the Star|Swati]]'''' which is a word derived from the language [[Sanskrit]].

* It is taught by a disciple of [[New Age]] [[guru]] [[Jose Arguelles]] on Arguelles‚Äô website that 3,000,000 years ago beings from Arcturus colonized the northern hemisphere of [[Mars]] and beings from [[Antares]] colonized the planet‚Ä≤s southern hemisphere.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.lawoftime.org/timeshipearth/arcturus.html Law of Time (Jose Arguelles‚Äô official website)--Timeship Earth 2013‚Äî&quot;Arcturus Remembered&quot;‚ÄîTransmission by ‚ÄúPan Agent‚Äù:]&lt;/ref&gt;

