      <text xml:space="preserve">'''Androphagi''' (Greek : &quot;·ºàŒΩŒ¥œÅŒøœÜŒ¨Œ≥ŒøŒπ&quot; for &quot;man-eaters&quot;) was an ancient nation of [[cannibalism|cannibals]] north of [[Scythia]] (according to [[Herodotus]]), probably in the forests between the upper waters of the [[Dneiper River|Dnepr]] and [[Don River, Russia|Don]]. These people may have assisted the [[Scythians]] when King [[Darius the Great]] led a Persian invasion into what is now Southern Russia to punish the Scythians for their raids into the [[Achaemenid Empire]].

Due to a [[false etymology]], a popular belief is that they were most likely Finns ‚Äì the obsolete name of  ''[[Nenets people|Nenets]]'' people, ''Samoyed'', has a similar meaning in Russian: &quot;self-eater&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;http://education.yahoo.com/reference/dictionary/entry/Samoyed&lt;/ref&gt;  See [[Nenets]].

The [[Gutasaga]] tells of the [[bl√≥ts]] on the island of Gotland in the Baltic Sea:

:Firi √æan tima oc lengi eptir si√æan. Tro√æu menn a hult. oc a hauga. wi. oc. stafgar√æa. oc a hai√æin gu√æ. blota√æu √æair synnum oc dydrum sinum Oc file√æi. mi√æ matj oc mundgati. √æet gier√æu √æair eptir wantro sinnj. land alt. haf√æi sir hoystu blotan mi√æ fulki. ellar haf√æi huer √æri√æiungr. sir. En smeri √æing haf√æu mindri blotan me√æ file√æi. matj. Oc mungati. sum haita su√ænautar. √æi et √æair su√æu allir saman. 

This is roughly translated:

:Before this time, and a long time thereafter, they believed in groves and barrows, sanctuaries, and sacred enclosures and in the pagan gods. They sacrificed (for?) their sons, daughters and cattle, and practiced bl√≥ts with food and drink. This they did due to their superstition. The whole country (the [[althing]]) had the largest [[bl√≥t]] with sacrifice of people, otherwise every trithing had its bl√≥t and smaller things had smaller bl√≥ts with cattle, food and drinks. They were called food-, or cooking-brethren, because they prepared the meals together.

